07625nam a22009255i 9780812290004DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132006pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979904939  a97808122900047 a10.9783/97808122900042doi  a(DE-B1597)449794  a(OCoLC)868967269  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aE18.82 -- N485 2005eb 7aHIS0360202bisacsh04a973.200aNew World Orders :bViolence, Sanction, and Authority in the Colonial Americas /ced. by Thomas J. Humphrey, John Smolenski. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2013] 4c©2006  a1 online resource (376 p.) :b6 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aEarly American Studies00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction. The Ordering of Authority in the Colonial Americas -- tPART I. Narrating Violence and Legality -- tIntroduction to Part I -- tChapter 1. Law's Wilderness: The Discourse of English Colonizing, the Violence of Intrusion, and the Failures of American History -- tChapter 2. Dialogical Encounters in a Space of Death -- tPART II. Authority and Intimate Violence -- tIntroduction to Part II -- tChapter 3. The Authority of Gender: Marital Discord and Social Order in Colonial Quito -- tChapter 4. Private and State Violence Against African Slaves in Lower Louisiana During the French Period, 1699-1769 -- tChapter 5. Violence or Sex? Constructions of Rape and Race in Early America -- tPART III. Colonial Space and Power -- tIntroduction to Part III -- tChapter 6. The Murder of Jacob Rabe: Contesting Dutch Colonial Authority in the Borderlands of Northeastern Brazil -- tChapter 7. Forging Cultures of Resistance on Two Colonial Frontiers: Northwestern Mexico and Eastern Bolivia -- tChapter 8. Sorcery and Sovereignty: Senecas, Citizens, and the Contest for Power and Authority on the Frontiers of the Early American Republic -- tPART IV. Race, Citizenship, and Colonial Identity -- tIntroduction to Part IV -- tChapter 9. Early Modern Spanish Citizenship: Inclusion and Exclusion in the Old and the New World -- tChapter 10. Natural Movements and Dangerous Spectacles: Beatings, Duels, and "Play" in Saint Domingue -- tChapter 11. Racial Passing: Informal and Official "Whiteness" in Colonial Spanish America -- tAfterword -- tNotes -- tContributors -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAs the geographic boundaries of early American history have expanded, so too have historians' attempts to explore the comparative dimensions of this history. At the same time, historians have struggled to find a conceptual framework flexible enough to incorporate the sweeping narratives of imperial history and the hidden narratives of social history into a broader, synthetic whole. No such paradigm that captures the two perspectives has yet emerged.New World Orders addresses these broad conceptual issues by reexamining the relationships among violence, sanction, and authority in the early modern Americas. More specifically, the essays in this volume explore the wide variety of legal and extralegal means—from state-sponsored executions to unsanctioned crowd actions—by which social order was maintained, with a particular emphasis on how extralegal sanctions were defined and used; how such sanctions related to legal forms of maintaining order; and how these patterns of sanction, embedded within other forms of colonialism and culture, created cultural, legal, social, or imperial spaces in the early Americas.With essays written by senior and junior scholars on the British, Spanish, Dutch, and French colonies, New World Orders presents one of the most comprehensive looks at the sweep of colonization in the Atlantic world. By juxtaposing case studies from Brazil, Venezuela, New York, California, Saint Domingue, and Louisiana with treatments of broader trends in Anglo-America or Spanish America more generally, the volume demonstrates the need to examine the questions of violence, sanction, and authority in hemispheric perspective.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aViolencezAmericaxHistory. 4aAmerican Studies. 7aHISTORY / United States / Colonial Period (1600-1775).2bisacsh  aAmerican History.  aAmerican Studies.1 aBlock, Sharon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDennis, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGauderman, Kimberly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerzog, Tamar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHumphrey, Thomas J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHumphrey, Thomas J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMeuwese, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aOgle, Gene E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPrice, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRadding, Cynthia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmolenski, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSmolenski, John, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aTomlins, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTwinam, Ann, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVidal, Cecile, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package American Historyz978311041349608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part